flowRoot.flowPara: The practice and reading of case studies conveys context-dependent knowldge, bringing urban practitioners to a higher level of expertise
Cases and comparative studies enable urban stakeholders to learn about mitigation actions and challenges from their peers
Assessments of the case study literature provide generalisable and context-specific mitigation solutions
Three ways to learn from case studies
Key problems in a time of big literature
Case studies have no consistent methods or system boundaries and are difficult to synthesize
Without systematic methods for literature selection and analysis, assessments are prone to biases
Urban stakeholders may be unsure who their peers are and which cities to learn from
The generalisability of single studies is unstated or unknown
A large volume of case studies is buried across hundreds of journals, risking duplication and hindering discovery
Build collaborative tools to render the urban case study literature transparent and searchable by city and topic, supported by automated methods
Structure case study knowledge and synthesis around typologies, enabling learning within groups of peers facing similar structural constraints
Use systematic evidence synthesis methods to aggregate knowledge from individual cases, while preserving context-dependency of solutions
Bottom-up, contextual assessment of challenges and solutions
Typology of cities: quantitative/qualitative understanding of urban differences
